# Chapter 13 — Latin percussion

Latin percussion is not one instrument. It is a family of
instruments that grew up together across the Caribbean and
Latin American world — Cuba, Puerto Rico, Brazil, the
Dominican Republic, Venezuela, Colombia, Peru — each with a
role in a shared rhythmic language that most Anglophone
listeners hear as \"the drums\" without hearing that the drums
are speaking to each other. The instruments were shaped by
the enslaved Africans who brought their music with them and
whose descendants developed the traditions in a world that
tried, and mostly failed, to erase them. To play Latin
percussion is to play into a conversation that started
centuries ago.

Latin percussion is not a section. It's a conversation.
Each drum has a role and each drum listens to the others.
Miss the listening and you're just banging.

## The core roster

The instruments most common in Afro-Cuban and Afro-Caribbean
music:

- **Congas** — tall single-headed drums, usually played in
  pairs (tumba + quinto) or threes. Played with bare hands.
- **Bongos** — smaller paired drums, hembra (larger) and
  macho (smaller), played on the lap.
- **Timbales** — shallow metal-shell drums with tuned skins,
  played with sticks.
- **Cowbell (cencerro)** — the metal bell that keeps the
  clave-adjacent pulse.
- **Claves** — two hardwood sticks that spell out the clave
  pattern itself.
- **Güiro** — a scraped gourd, used for texture and 8th-note
  fill.
- **Maracas** — paired shakers, 16th-note groove.
- **Cajón** — Peruvian wooden box, played by sitting on it
  and slapping the face.
- **Surdo** — Brazilian bass drum, carried, played with a
  mallet, the heartbeat of samba.
- **Pandeiro** — Brazilian tambourine, played with the
  fingers and palm; every samba's core percussion.
- **Repinique / repique** — Brazilian small drum used to
  call the band into and out of sections.

```scheme
(define latin-percussion-roster
  '((congas    \"tall skins, hands, tumba/quinto/conga\")
    (bongos    \"small paired lap drums, hembra/macho\")
    (timbales  \"shallow tuned metal shells, sticks\")
    (cowbell   \"cencerro — metal bell, pulse\")
    (claves    \"hardwood sticks, spell the clave\")
    (güiro     \"scraped gourd, texture\")
    (maracas   \"paired shakers, 16th-note fill\")
    (cajón     \"Peruvian wooden box, hand slaps\")
    (surdo     \"Brazilian bass drum, heartbeat\")
    (pandeiro  \"Brazilian tambourine, samba core\")
    (repique   \"Brazilian small drum, call figure\")))
```

## Clave — the underlying pattern

The clave is the two-bar rhythmic phrase that underlies most
Afro-Cuban music. Two shapes, played on claves (the
instrument), signal which side is which:

```scheme
;; 3-2 son clave — three strikes in bar 1, two in bar 2
(define son-clave-3-2
  '((bar-1 1 0 0 1 0 0 1 0)
    (bar-2 0 0 1 0 1 0 0 0)))

;; 2-3 son clave — reversed
(define son-clave-2-3
  '((bar-1 0 0 1 0 1 0 0 0)
    (bar-2 1 0 0 1 0 0 1 0)))
```

Every other rhythm in an Afro-Cuban tune orients to the
clave. The conga's tumbao pattern implies it. The bongo's
martillo pattern nests around it. The timbales' cascara
pattern locks with it. When any instrument's phrase
\"crosses the clave\" (implies the wrong shape), the whole
band feels it — the phrase gets fixed or the section is
called wrong.

## Roles inside a Cuban rhythm section

- The **conga** plays tumbao (a bass-heavy repeating pattern
  that hooks into the clave's off-beats).
- The **bongos** play martillo during verses (a steady
  triplet-adjacent pattern) and switch to cencerro fills
  during choruses.
- The **timbales** hold the section together with cascara
  during verses and drive the choruses with abanico fills.
- The **cowbell** holds the strong beat during choruses.
- The **claves** spell the clave itself.
- The **güiro** and **maracas** fill the higher-frequency
  texture — 8th and 16th notes constantly present.

Each instrument's job is small. The whole is much larger
than any part. That \"everyone plays their small role and
listens\" is what Latin percussion teaches at every level.

## A Brazilian samba section

Different family, similar principle:

- **Surdo primeiro** (largest) — beat 2 (the samba
  heartbeat).
- **Surdo segundo** — beat 1.
- **Surdo terceiro** — improvised responses.
- **Caixa** — snare-adjacent 16th-note groove.
- **Repique** — call figures and fills.
- **Tamborim** — small handheld drum, palm-slap 16ths.
- **Agogô** — twin cowbells at contrasting pitches.
- **Cuíca** — friction drum with the whistling squeak.
- **Pandeiro** — the core groove.

The samba school is a rhythm section of hundreds of players,
each with a small role, walking down the street. The
conversation scales to any size because every role knows
what the roles next to it are.

## Cross-instrument note

The instruments in this chapter compose with the drum kit
covered in chapter 4. A kit drummer holding time while
congas play tumbao is doing the same work a bassist does
under a lead sheet — the kit is the tune's spine, the congas
are the tune's ornament. She reads which is which when she
scores.

## Editorial note

The vocabulary in this chapter comes with a responsibility.
The traditions were preserved through generations of players
who taught each other by ear and hand. Every word above —
tumbao, martillo, cascara, tumba, quinto — carries a lineage.
She doesn't use these words as decoration. She uses them
because they name specific things a specific player would
recognize, and misusing them is a way of not listening. Same
with the Brazilian vocabulary: surdo primeiro is a role, not
a marketing term. When she talks about Latin percussion, she
speaks with the vocabulary of the tradition, not around it.
")
